Sharing of debts, namely finances

Mauritians tend to spend money aimlessly, and Mauritius’ consumer debt is quite high compared to the rest of the world.It’s not surprising, then, that some localized cultural norms around the beliefs that marriages should be a shared financial responsibility.

Post-marital property disputes

The government and legislature in Mauritius have developed a myriad of laws aimed at protecting the spouse and children from serious post-marital financial hardships.

On the other hand, civil actions usually favour survivors of the deceased over any children.

Savings, for some people, are an unsafe choice

Similarly to the country’s consumer debt, saving is almost always a good idea.

But in Mauritius, there exists a culture that saving money is dangerous and better spent elsewhere.Therefore, when it comes to what someone might consider assets when calculating a financial settlement, it becomes quite difficult.

It is difficult to predict if and when a couple might divorce

Mauritius has instituted a mediation option which is mandatory before a spouse can file for divorce.

Although the spouse may have filed for divorce,\ delays to the process may be necessary if the divorce complaint is filed.
